hands_on_practices.problem:
A particle of mass $m$ is confined to a one-dimensional infinite potential well (one-dimensional box) with perfectly rigid walls at $x=0$ and $x=L$, where the potential is $V(x)=0$ for $0<x<L$ and $V(x)=\infty$ otherwise. The particle is in the normalized stationary state with quantum number $n=1$. The normalized spatial wavefunction for this state is
$$
\psi_{1}(x)=
\begin{cases}
\sqrt{\frac{2}{L}}\,\sin\!\left(\frac{\pi x}{L}\right), & 0<x<L \\
0, & \text{otherwise}
\end{cases}
$$
Using the probabilistic interpretation of the wavefunction, determine the probability of finding the particle between $x=L/4$ and $x=3L/4$. Express your final answer as a closed-form expression (no numerical approximation). Do not include units.
